\"left\"|{{flagicon|FR Yugoslavia}} [[Du\u0161an Jovanovi\u0107 (footballer)|Du\u0161an Jovanovi\u0107]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]\n|17\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|5\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Greece}} [[Michalis Klokidis]]\n|align=\"left\"|[[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|14\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|{{flagicon|Brazil}} Marcelo\n|align=\"left\"|[[Edessaikos F.C.|Edessaikos]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Teams by region ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Region\n!Number of teams\n!Teams\n|-\n|[[Macedonia (Greece)|Macedonia]]||align=center|7||align=center|[[Apollon Kalamarias F.C.|Apollon Kalamarias]], [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]], [[Doxa Drama F.C.|Doxa Drama]], [[Edessaikos F.C.|Edessaikos]], [[ILTEX Lykoi F.C.|ILTEX Lykoi]], [[Kastoria F.C.|Kastoria]], [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]]\n|-\n|[[Attica]]||align=center|4||align=center|[[Doxa Vyronas F.C.|Doxa Vyronas]], [[Ethnikos Asteras F.C.|Ethnikos Asteras]], [[Kallithea F.C.|Kallithea]], [[Panelefsiniakos F.C.|Panelefsiniakos]]\n|-\n|[[Thessaly]]||align=center|4||align=center|[[Anagennisi Karditsa F.C.|Anagennisi Karditsa]], [[AE Larissa FC|Larissa]], [[Niki Volos F.C.|Niki Volos]], [[Trikala F.C.|Trikala]]\n|-\n|[[Central Greece]]||align=center|2||align=center|[[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]], [[Panetolikos F.C.|Panetolikos]]\n|-\n|[[Peloponnese]]||align=center|1||align=center|[[Panargiakos F.C.|Panargiakos]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk2hist.html#98 RSSSF.com]\n\n{{Football League (Greece) seasons}}\n{{1997\u201398 in Greek football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1997-98 Beta Ethniki}}\n[[Category:Second level Greek football league seasons]]\n[[Category:1997\u201398 in European second tier association football leagues|Greece]]\n[[Category:1997\u201398 in Greek football|2]]\n", "name_user": "Jolicnikola", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTop scorers", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997%E2%80%9398_Beta_Ethniki"}
{"title_page": "Offset (computer science)", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn [[computer science]], an '''offset''' within an [[Array data structure|array]] or other [[data structure]] object is an [[integer (computer science)|integer]] indicating the distance (displacement) between the beginning of the object and a given element or point, presumably within the same object. The concept of a gbgbg distance is valid only if all elements of the object are of the same size (typically given in [[Byte-addressable|bytes]] or [[Word-addressable|words]]).\n\nFor example, in <code>A</code> as an [[Array data type|array]] of characters containing <code>\"abcdef\"</code>, the fourth element containing the character <code>'d'</code> has an offset of three from the start of <code>A</code>.\n\n== In assembly language ==\nIn [[computer engineering]] and low-level programming (such as [[assembly language]]), an '''offset''' usually denotes the number of address locations added to a [[base address]] in order to get to a specific [[absolute address]]. In this (original) meaning of offset, only the basic address unit, usually the 8-bit [[byte]], is used to specify the offset's size. In this context an offset is sometimes called a '''relative address'''.\n\nIn [[IBM System/360]] instructions, a 12-bit offset embedded within certain instructions provided a range of between 0 and 4096 bytes. For example, within an unconditional branch instruction (X'47F0Fxxx'), the xxx 12bit hexadecimal offset provided the byte offset from the base register (15) to branch to. An odd offset would cause a [[program check]] (unless the base register itself also contained an odd address) - since instructions had to be aligned on half-word boundaries to execute without a program or hardware [[interrupt]]\n\nThe previous example describes an indirect way to address to a memory location in the format of segment:offset. For example, assume we want to refer to memory location 0xF867.  One way this can be accomplished is by first defining a segment with beginning address 0xF000, and then defining an offset of 0x0867.  Further, we are also allowed to shift the hexadecimal segment to reach the final absolute memory address. One thing to note here is that we can reach our final absolute address in many ways. \n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offset (Computer Science)}}\n[[Category:Computer memory]]\n\n\n{{compsci-stub}}\n\n[[de:Speicheradresse#Segmentierte Adressen]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=October 2015}}\n\nIn [[computer science]], an '''offset''' within an [[Array data structure|array]] or other [[data structure]] object is an [[integer (computer science)|integer]] indicating the distance (displacement) between the beginning of the object and a given element or point, presumably within the same object. The concept of a distance is valid only if all elements of the object are of the same size (typically given in [[Byte-addressable|bytes]] or [[Word-addressable|words]]).\n\nFor example, in <code>A</code> as an [[Array data type|array]] of characters containing <code>\"abcdef\"</code>, the fourth element containing the character <code>'d'</code> has an offset of three from the start of <code>A</code>.\n\n== In assembly language ==\nIn [[computer engineering]] and low-level programming (such as [[assembly language]]), an '''offset''' usually denotes the number of address locations added to a [[base address]] in order to get to a specific [[absolute address]]. In this (original) meaning of offset, only the basic address unit, usually the 8-bit [[byte]], is used to specify the offset's size. In this context an offset is sometimes called a '''relative address'''.\n\nIn [[IBM System/360]] instructions, a 12-bit offset embedded within certain instructions provided a range of between 0 and 4096 bytes. For example, within an unconditional branch instruction (X'47F0Fxxx'), the xxx 12bit hexadecimal offset provided the byte offset from the base register (15) to branch to. An odd offset would cause a [[program check]] (unless the base register itself also contained an odd address) - since instructions had to be aligned on half-word boundaries to execute without a program or hardware [[interrupt]]\n\nThe previous example describes an indirect way to address to a memory location in the format of segment:offset. For example, assume we want to refer to memory location 0xF867.  One way this can be accomplished is by first defining a segment with beginning address 0xF000, and then defining an offset of 0x0867.  Further, we are also allowed to shift the hexadecimal segment to reach the final absolute memory address. One thing to note here is that we can reach our final absolute address in many ways.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Offset (Computer Science)}}\n[[Category:Computer memory]]\n\n\n{{compsci-stub}}\n\n[[de:Speicheradresse#Segmentierte Adressen]]\n", "name_user": "74.140.199.120", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Offset_(computer_science)"}
{"title_page": "Teemu Tainio", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish football coach and former player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Teemu Tainio\n| image          = TeemuTainio (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = 300\n| caption        = Tainio playing for the [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011\n| fullname       = <!-- if different -->\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1979|11|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tornio]], Finland\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| position       = [[Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[FC Haka]] (manager)\n| youthyears1    = 1994\u20131995 |youthclubs1 = [[TP-47]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20131997 |clubs1 = [[FC Haka]]                                       |caps1 = 46  |goals1 = 14\n| years2         = 1997\u20132005 |clubs2 = [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]]                            |caps2 = 150 |goals2 = 14\n| years3         = 2005\u20132008 |clubs3 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]      |caps3 = 61  |goals3 = 3\n| years4         = 2008\u20132010 |clubs4 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]                  |caps4 = 21  |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2009\u20132010 |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan) |caps5 = 6   |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2010\u20132011 |clubs6 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]                                 |caps6 = 2   |goals6 = 0\n| years7         = 2011\u20132012 |clubs7 = [[New York Red Bulls]]                            |caps7 = 42  |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 2013\u22122014 |clubs8 = [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK Helsinki]]        |caps8 = 36  |goals8 = 3\n| totalcaps      = 364 |totalgoals = 34\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132014 |nationalteam1 = [[Finland national football team|Finland]] |nationalcaps1 = 64 |nationalgoals1 = 6\n| club-update    = 28 October 2015\n| nationalteam-update = 12 October 2014\n| manageryears1  = 2018\u2013      |managerclubs1 = [[FC Haka]]\n}}\n\n'''Teemu Tainio''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8te\u02d0mu \u02c8t\u0251inio}}; born 27 November 1979) is a Finnish [[association football|football]] coach and former player. He is the current head coach of [[FC Haka]]. He began his career with his local club, [[TP-47]], before moving to [[FC Haka]] in 1996. A year later, he moved to France to play for [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]]. After eight years there, he joined English club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], where he spent three years before joining [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. After a loan spell with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] during the 2009\u201310 season, he moved to Dutch club [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], before joining the [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011. After two seasons in the United States, he returned to Finland to finish his career with [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK]].\n\nHe mostly played in a variety of [[Midfielder|midfield]] positions during his career, and also at [[right-back]] under [[Juande Ramos]] at Tottenham.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nTainio was born in [[Tornio]]. He was promoted to the first team of his home-town club [[TP-47]] in [[Kakkonen]], Finland's third tier, at the age of fourteen. He was signed by [[Veikkausliiga]] club [[FC Haka]] for the 1996 season. Following a trial at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in March 1997, Tainio joined French club [[AJ Auxerre]] in 1997, and spent eight years at the club. He won the [[Coupe de France]] with Auxerre twice, and also gained [[UEFA Champions League]] experience. While with Auxerre, Tainio appeared in 204 official matches and scored 19 goals.<ref>[http://www.histoaja.free.fr/joueurs/tainio.htm Profile at Auxerre's histoaja.free.fr Tainio with Auxerre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119113154/http://www.histoaja.free.fr/joueurs/tainio.htm |date=19 November 2010 }}{{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nWith Tainio's contract with Auxerre due to expire in 2005, he became available on a [[free transfer (football)|free transfer]]. In January 2005, it was announced that he would move to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on a seven-year deal in the summer of 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spurs sign Tainio |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/2325060/spurs-sign-tainio |website=SkySports |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> He became a regular for Spurs in his first season, playing in various midfield positions.\n\nHe scored his first goal for his new club in December 2005 against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] during a Premiership match at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4560326.stm |title=Tottenham 2\u20130 Newcastle |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=31 December 2005 |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> Tainio was one of ten Spurs squad members struck down by a virus on the evening of 6 May 2006 before their crucial final game of the season against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0516/spurs.html |work=RT\u00c9 News |title=Tests clear hotel in Spurs food poisoning incident |date=16 May 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504062526/http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0516/spurs.html |archivedate=4 May 2007 }}</ref> He nevertheless played in the match, which Spurs lost, missing out on a place in the Champions League.\n\nHe scored his second Spurs goal on 9 December 2006, the third goal in the 5\u20131 home win against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6201484.stm |title= Tottenham 5\u20131 Charlton |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=9 December 2006 |accessdate=3 November 2009 |first=Sam  |last=Lyon}}</ref> His third goal for the club was an equaliser against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] to make the score 2\u20132 on 4 March 2007. Spurs went on to win the game 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6392467.stm |title=West Ham 3\u20134 Tottenham |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=4 March 2007 |accessdate=3 November 2009 |first=Paul |last=Fletcher}}</ref>\n\nTainio won the 2008 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] when Tottenham took a 2\u20131 extra-time win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the final played on 24 February 2008. He came on as a substitute in the 75th minute when the score was 1\u20131. He then was booked with five more minutes left in the game for time wasting on a throw in.<ref>[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Teemu+Tainio+wins+League+Cup+winners+medal/1135234337787 Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition \u2013 Sport<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\nHe joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 23 July 2008 for an undisclosed fee. He became their first summer signing and the first Finnish player ever for Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Headlines/0,,12306~1349935,00.html|title=Sunderland complete Tainio signing|author=Martin Walker|publisher=SAFC.com|date=22 July 2008|accessdate=24 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/?page_id=15265|title=Tainio Completes Sunderland Move|author=www.safc.com|publisher=Premierleague.com|date=22 July 2008|accessdate=24 August 2008}}</ref>\nHe scored his first goal for Sunderland in a second round League Cup game at [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] on 24 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8203066.stm|title=Norwich 1 \u2013 4 Sunderland|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2009}}</ref> He left Sunderland on 31 August 2010, when the club terminated his contract by mutual consent.\n\n====Birmingham City (loan)====\nTainio joined [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 1 September 2009, on loan for the remainder of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blues.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~1784805,00.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721145059/http://www.blues.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~1784805,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2012|title=It's Teemu Time|publisher=Birmingham City F.C.|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=1 September 2009}}</ref> Having recovered from a calf injury sustained on international duty,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/midlands-football/2009/09/09/birmingham-city-midfielder-teemu-tainio-s-calf-injury-not-serious-97319-24644201/ |title=Birmingham City midfielder Teemu Tainio's calf injury 'not serious' |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=9 September 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> he made his debut for the club on 13 September in a 1\u20130 home defeat in the [[Birmingham derby]] against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], in which he produced a good performance in a less-familiar role at right-back.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/birmingham-city-fc/birmingham-city-fc-news/2009/09/14/birmingham-city-v-aston-villa-colin-tattum-s-blues-player-ratings-and-match-stats-97319-24680633/ |title=Birmingham City v Aston Villa: Colin Tattum's Blues player ratings and match stats |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=14 September 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Ajax===\nTainio signed a one-year contract with [[AFC Ajax]] on the very same day after he was released by Sunderland. At Ajax, he rejoined his former Tottenham coach, [[Martin Jol]].<ref>[http://www.ajax.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwsarchief/Nieuws-artikel/Ajax-contracteert-Teemu-Tainio.htm Ajax contracteert Teemu Tainio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903160455/http://www.ajax.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwsarchief/Nieuws-artikel/Ajax-contracteert-Teemu-Tainio.htm |date=3 September 2010 }} {{in lang|nl}}</ref> He made his Ajax debut on 11 September 2010, playing the last five minutes as a substitute for [[Demy de Zeeuw]] in a 2\u20130 victory over [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]]. He also made appearance in the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|2010\u201311 Champions League]], playing the last 21 minutes against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the 2\u20130 away loss match in the group stage.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000118/match=2002821/index.html Real Madrid - Ajax 2-0] {{in lang|en}}</ref> After making only five official appearances while with Ajax, Tainio accepted an offer from [[Major League Soccer]] side [[New York Red Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbyives.net/soccer_by_ives/2011/03/mls-ticker-fc-dallas-signs-castillo-portland-signs-perlaza-and-red-bulls-add-tainio-1.html|title=MLS Ticker: FC Dallas lands Castillo, Portland signs Perlaza and Red Bulls add Tainio|date=7 March 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===New York Red Bulls===\nTainio joined New York Red Bulls during their pre-season training for the 2011 [[Major League Soccer]] season. He became the first Finn to sign for the team formerly known as the New York/New Jersey Metrostars when the club officially signed him on 9 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/news/2011/03/red-bulls-sign-teemu-tainio-and-stephen-keel|title=Tainio signs with New York|publisher=}}</ref> He made his official debut for New York on 19 March 2011, in the Red Bulls' 2011 MLS season opener, a 1\u20130 victory over [[Seattle Sounders FC]], assisting on [[Juan Agudelo]]'s game-winning goal. He has quickly become a fan favorite early in the season with multiple assists and good play to his name.<ref>[http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/agudelos-first-mls-goal-difference-vs-seattle Tainio's assist helps NY in victory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322041323/http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/agudelos-first-mls-goal-difference-vs-seattle |date=22 March 2011 }}</ref> On 15 November 2012, Tainio, along with teammates [[Jan Gunnar Solli]], [[Bill Gaudette]], and [[Jose Angulo]] were all denied contract extensions, thus ending their tenure at New York.\n\n===HJK Helsinki===\nOn 2 January 2013, it was announced that the 33-year-old Tainio had signed a two-year contract with [[2012 Veikkausliiga|the reigning Finnish champions]], [[HJK Helsinki]].<ref>[http://www.hjk.fi/uutiset/1-1367/Teme+Tainio+Klubin+keskikent%C3%A4lle Teme Tainio Klubin keskikent\u00e4lle] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> On 19 June 2013, he scored his first goal for HJK, in a 4\u22122 away win over [[MYPA]]. This was his first goal since 24 August 2009.\nOn 14 February 2015, Tainio announced his retirement as a player.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finland's Teemu Tainio calls time on playing career |url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=2209471.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Teemu Tainio.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Tainio with [[Finland national football team|Finland]]]]\nTainio made his debut for the [[Finland national football team|Finnish national team]] on 5 February 1998 against\n[[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]], and was a regular for the team through most of the 2000s. After signing with [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011, Tainio announced that he might retire at the international level, citing the long-distance flights and time difference between the States and Finland.<ref>[http://www.palloliitto.fi/viestinta/?num=181874 {{in lang|fi}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720191711/http://www.palloliitto.fi/viestinta/?num=181874 |date=20 July 2011 }}</ref> After a two-year hiatus, Tainio made his comeback to the international team, immediately after his contract with the Red Bulls expired.\n\n==Managerial career==\nOn 1 November 2018, Tainio was appointed as head coach of [[Ykk\u00f6nen]] side [[FC Haka]], having previously worked as a coach at the side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fchaka.fi/?p=7532|title=Teemu Tainio valmis uusiin haasteisiin|publisher=[[FC Haka]]|date=1 November 2018|accessdate=5 June 2019|language=Finnish}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International goals===\n''Finland's score first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Location !! Opponent !! Score!! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 1 September 2001 || [[Tirana]], Albania || {{fb|ALB}} || 2\u20130 || Win || [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 2. || 6 September 2003 || [[Baku]], Azerbaijan || {{fb|AZE}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]]\n|-\n| 3. || 11 October 2003 || [[Tampere]], Finland || {{fb|CAN}} || 3\u20132 || Win || Friendly\n|-\n| 4. || 16 November 2003 || [[Houston]], USA || {{fb|HON}} || 2\u20131 || Win || Friendly\n|-\n| 5. || 13 October 2004 || [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands || {{fb|NED}} || 1\u20133 || Loss || [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 6. || 22 August 2007 || Tampere, Finland || {{fb|KAZ}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===International===\n\n{{updated|14 February 2015}}<ref>{{NFT player|id=2402|accessdate= }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Finland national football team|Finland national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1998||3||0\n|-\n|1999||1||0\n|-\n|2000||3||0\n|-\n|2001||4||1\n|-\n|2002||6||0\n|-\n|2003||6||3\n|-\n|2004||2||1\n|-\n|2005||8||0\n|-\n|2006||2||0\n|-\n|2007||6||1\n|-\n|2008||5||0\n|-\n|2009||4||0\n|-\n|2010||2||0\n|-\n|2011||0||0\n|-\n|2012||0||0\n|-\n|2013||9||0\n|-\n|2014||3||0\n|-\n!Total||64||6\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''FC Haka'''\n*[[Finnish Cup]]: [[1997 Finnish Cup|1997]]\n\n'''Auxerre'''\n*[[Intertoto Cup]]: [[1997 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1997]]\n*[[Coupe de France]]: [[2005 Coupe de France Final|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''Tottenham Hotspur'''\n*[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]: [[2007\u201308 Football League Cup|2007\u201308]]\n\n'''Ajax'''\n*[[Eredivisie]]: [[2010\u201311 Eredivisie|2010\u201311]]\n\n'''HJK'''\n*[[Veikkausliiga]]: [[2013 Veikkausliiga|2013]], [[2014 Veikkausliiga|2014]]\n*[[Finnish Cup]]: [[2014 Finnish Cup|2014]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006191137/http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/players/teemu-tainio |date=6 October 2011 |title=Profile at [http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/ newyorkredbulls.com]}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n*{{FIFA player|185932}}\n* {{UEFA player|26142}}\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525154506/http://www.palloliitto.fi/maajoukkueet/miesten_a-maajoukkue/pelaajat/tainio_teemu/ |date=25 May 2011 |title=Profile at FA of Finland's official website}}\n*{{Webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224090014/http://soccernet.espn.go.com/players/profile?id=10558&cc=5739 |date=24 December 2007 |title=Profile at ESPNsoccernet.com}}\n*{{Lequipe|2958}}\n*{{NFT player|id=2402}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tainio, Teemu}}\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Tornio]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Finnish footballers]]\n[[Category:Finland international footballers]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in the United States]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate sportspeople in the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:FC Haka players]]\n[[Category:AJ Auxerre players]]\n[[Category:Tottenham Hotspur F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Birmingham City F.C. players]]\n[[Category:AFC Ajax players]]\n[[Category:New York Red Bulls players]]\n[[Category:Veikkausliiga players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 1 players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Major League Soccer players]]\n[[Category:Finnish expatriate sportspeople in the United States]]\n[[Category:TP-47 players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish football coach and former player}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Teemu Tainio\n| image          = TeemuTainio (cropped).jpg\n| image_size     = 300\n| caption        = Tainio playing for the [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011\n| fullname       = <!-- if different -->\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1979|11|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Tornio]], Finland\n| height         = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}\n| position       = [[Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[FC Haka]] (manager)\n| youthyears1    = 1994\u20131995 |youthclubs1 = [[TP-47]]\n| years1         = 1996\u20131997 |clubs1 = [[FC Haka]]                                       |caps1 = 46  |goals1 = 14\n| years2         = 1997\u20132005 |clubs2 = [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]]                            |caps2 = 150 |goals2 = 14\n| years3         = 2005\u20132008 |clubs3 = [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]]      |caps3 = 61  |goals3 = 3\n| years4         = 2008\u20132010 |clubs4 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]                  |caps4 = 21  |goals4 = 0\n| years5         = 2009\u20132010 |clubs5 = \u2192 [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] (loan) |caps5 = 6   |goals5 = 0\n| years6         = 2010\u20132011 |clubs6 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]                                 |caps6 = 2   |goals6 = 0\n| years7         = 2011\u20132012 |clubs7 = [[New York Red Bulls]]                            |caps7 = 42  |goals7 = 0\n| years8         = 2013\u22122014 |clubs8 = [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK Helsinki]]        |caps8 = 36  |goals8 = 3\n| totalcaps      = 364 |totalgoals = 34\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132014 |nationalteam1 = [[Finland national football team|Finland]] |nationalcaps1 = 64 |nationalgoals1 = 6\n| club-update    = 28 October 2015\n| nationalteam-update = 12 October 2014\n| manageryears1  = 2018\u2013      |managerclubs1 = [[FC Haka]]\n}}\n\n'''Teemu Tainio''' ({{IPA-fi|\u02c8te\u02d0mu \u02c8t\u0251inio}}; born 27 November 1979) is a Finnish [[association football|football]] coach and former player. He is the current head coach of [[FC Haka]]. He began his career with his local club, [[TP-47]], before moving to [[FC Haka]] in 1996. A year later, he moved to France to play for [[AJ Auxerre|Auxerre]]. After eight years there, he joined English club [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], where he spent three years before joining [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]. After a loan spell with [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] during the 2009\u201310 season, he moved to Dutch club [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]], before joining the [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011. After two seasons in the United States, he returned to Finland to finish his career with [[Helsingin Jalkapalloklubi|HJK]].\n\nHe mostly played in a variety of [[Midfielder|midfield]] positions during his career, and also at [[right-back]] under [[Juande Ramos]] at Tottenham.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Early career===\nTainio was born in [[Tornio]]. He was promoted to the first team of his home-town club [[TP-47]] in [[Kakkonen]], Finland's third tier, at the age of fourteen. He was signed by [[Veikkausliiga]] club [[FC Haka]] for the 1996 season. Following a trial at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] in March 1997, Tainio joined French club [[AJ Auxerre]] in 1997, and spent eight years at the club. He won the [[Coupe de France]] with Auxerre twice, and also gained [[UEFA Champions League]] experience. While with Auxerre, Tainio appeared in 204 official matches and scored 19 goals.<ref>[http://www.histoaja.free.fr/joueurs/tainio.htm Profile at Auxerre's histoaja.free.fr Tainio with Auxerre] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119113154/http://www.histoaja.free.fr/joueurs/tainio.htm |date=19 November 2010 }}{{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n\n===Tottenham Hotspur===\nWith Tainio's contract with Auxerre due to expire in 2005, he became available on a [[free transfer (football)|free transfer]]. In January 2005, it was announced that he would move to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] on a seven-year deal in the summer of 2005.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spurs sign Tainio |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11675/2325060/spurs-sign-tainio |website=SkySports |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref> He became a regular for Spurs in his first season, playing in various midfield positions.\n\nHe scored his first goal for his new club in December 2005 against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] during a Premiership match at [[White Hart Lane]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4560326.stm |title=Tottenham 2\u20130 Newcastle |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=31 December 2005 |accessdate=3 November 2009}}</ref> Tainio was one of ten Spurs squad members struck down by a virus on the evening of 6 May 2006 before their crucial final game of the season against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0516/spurs.html |work=RT\u00c9 News |title=Tests clear hotel in Spurs food poisoning incident |date=16 May 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504062526/http://www.rte.ie/sport/2006/0516/spurs.html |archivedate=4 May 2007 }}</ref> He nevertheless played in the match, which Spurs lost, missing out on a place in the Champions League.\n\nHe scored his second Spurs goal on 9 December 2006, the third goal in the 5\u20131 home win against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6201484.stm |title= Tottenham 5\u20131 Charlton |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=9 December 2006 |accessdate=3 November 2009 |first=Sam  |last=Lyon}}</ref> His third goal for the club was an equaliser against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham]] to make the score 2\u20132 on 4 March 2007. Spurs went on to win the game 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/6392467.stm |title=West Ham 3\u20134 Tottenham |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=4 March 2007 |accessdate=3 November 2009 |first=Paul |last=Fletcher}}</ref>\n\nTainio won the 2008 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] when Tottenham took a 2\u20131 extra-time win over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] at [[Wembley Stadium]] in the final played on 24 February 2008. He came on as a substitute in the 75th minute when the score was 1\u20131. He then was booked with five more minutes left in the game for time wasting on a throw in.<ref>[http://www.hs.fi/english/article/Teemu+Tainio+wins+League+Cup+winners+medal/1135234337787 Helsingin Sanomat \u2013 International Edition \u2013 Sport<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\nHe joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] on 23 July 2008 for an undisclosed fee. He became their first summer signing and the first Finnish player ever for Sunderland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Headlines/0,,12306~1349935,00.html|title=Sunderland complete Tainio signing|author=Martin Walker|publisher=SAFC.com|date=22 July 2008|accessdate=24 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/?page_id=15265|title=Tainio Completes Sunderland Move|author=www.safc.com|publisher=Premierleague.com|date=22 July 2008|accessdate=24 August 2008}}</ref>\nHe scored his first goal for Sunderland in a second round League Cup game at [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich]] on 24 August 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8203066.stm|title=Norwich 1 \u2013 4 Sunderland|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=24 August 2009}}</ref> He left Sunderland on 31 August 2010, when the club terminated his contract by mutual consent.\n\n====Birmingham City (loan)====\nTainio joined [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 1 September 2009, on loan for the remainder of the 2009\u201310 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blues.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~1784805,00.html|archive-url=https://archive.is/20120721145059/http://www.blues.premiumtv.co.uk/page/News/NewsDetail/0,,10412~1784805,00.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 July 2012|title=It's Teemu Time|publisher=Birmingham City F.C.|date=1 September 2009|accessdate=1 September 2009}}</ref> Having recovered from a calf injury sustained on international duty,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/midlands-football/2009/09/09/birmingham-city-midfielder-teemu-tainio-s-calf-injury-not-serious-97319-24644201/ |title=Birmingham City midfielder Teemu Tainio's calf injury 'not serious' |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=9 September 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref> he made his debut for the club on 13 September in a 1\u20130 home defeat in the [[Birmingham derby]] against [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], in which he produced a good performance in a less-familiar role at right-back.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.net/birmingham-sport/birmingham-city-fc/birmingham-city-fc-news/2009/09/14/birmingham-city-v-aston-villa-colin-tattum-s-blues-player-ratings-and-match-stats-97319-24680633/ |title=Birmingham City v Aston Villa: Colin Tattum's Blues player ratings and match stats |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |first=Colin |last=Tattum |date=14 September 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Ajax===\nTainio signed a one-year contract with [[AFC Ajax]] on the very same day after he was released by Sunderland. At Ajax, he rejoined his former Tottenham coach, [[Martin Jol]].<ref>[http://www.ajax.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwsarchief/Nieuws-artikel/Ajax-contracteert-Teemu-Tainio.htm Ajax contracteert Teemu Tainio] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100903160455/http://www.ajax.nl/Nieuws/Nieuwsarchief/Nieuws-artikel/Ajax-contracteert-Teemu-Tainio.htm |date=3 September 2010 }} {{in lang|nl}}</ref> He made his Ajax debut on 11 September 2010, playing the last five minutes as a substitute for [[Demy de Zeeuw]] in a 2\u20130 victory over [[Willem II (football club)|Willem II]]. He also made appearance in the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|2010\u201311 Champions League]], playing the last 21 minutes against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the 2\u20130 away loss match in the group stage.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000118/match=2002821/index.html Real Madrid - Ajax 2-0] {{in lang|en}}</ref> After making only five official appearances while with Ajax, Tainio accepted an offer from [[Major League Soccer]] side [[New York Red Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerbyives.net/soccer_by_ives/2011/03/mls-ticker-fc-dallas-signs-castillo-portland-signs-perlaza-and-red-bulls-add-tainio-1.html|title=MLS Ticker: FC Dallas lands Castillo, Portland signs Perlaza and Red Bulls add Tainio|date=7 March 2011|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===New York Red Bulls===\nTainio joined New York Red Bulls during their pre-season training for the 2011 [[Major League Soccer]] season. He became the first Finn to sign for the team formerly known as the New York/New Jersey Metrostars when the club officially signed him on 9 March 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newyorkredbulls.com/news/2011/03/red-bulls-sign-teemu-tainio-and-stephen-keel|title=Tainio signs with New York|publisher=}}</ref> He made his official debut for New York on 19 March 2011, in the Red Bulls' 2011 MLS season opener, a 1\u20130 victory over [[Seattle Sounders FC]], assisting on [[Juan Agudelo]]'s game-winning goal. He has quickly become a fan favorite early in the season with multiple assists and good play to his name.<ref>[http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/agudelos-first-mls-goal-difference-vs-seattle Tainio's assist helps NY in victory] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322041323/http://www.mlssoccer.com/matchcenter-recap/agudelos-first-mls-goal-difference-vs-seattle |date=22 March 2011 }}</ref> On 15 November 2012, Tainio, along with teammates [[Jan Gunnar Solli]], [[Bill Gaudette]], and [[Jose Angulo]] were all denied contract extensions, thus ending their tenure at New York.\n\n===HJK Helsinki===\nOn 2 January 2013, it was announced that the 33-year-old Tainio had signed a two-year contract with [[2012 Veikkausliiga|the reigning Finnish champions]], [[HJK Helsinki]].<ref>[http://www.hjk.fi/uutiset/1-1367/Teme+Tainio+Klubin+keskikent%C3%A4lle Teme Tainio Klubin keskikent\u00e4lle] {{in lang|fi}}</ref> On 19 June 2013, he scored his first goal for HJK, in a 4\u22122 away win over [[MYPA]]. This was his first goal since 24 August 2009.\nOn 14 February 2015, Tainio announced his retirement as a player.<ref>{{cite web |title=Finland's Teemu Tainio calls time on playing career |url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=2209471.html |website=UEFA.com |accessdate=4 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n[[File:Teemu Tainio.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Tainio with [[Finland national football team|Finland]]]]\nTainio made his debut for the [[Finland national football team|Finnish national team]] on 5 February 1998 against\n[[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]], and was a regular for the team through most of the 2000s. After signing with [[New York Red Bulls]] in 2011, Tainio announced that he might retire at the international level, citing the long distance flights and time difference between the States and Finland.<ref>[http://www.palloliitto.fi/viestinta/?num=181874 {{in lang|fi}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720191711/http://www.palloliitto.fi/viestinta/?num=181874 |date=20 July 2011 }}</ref> After a two-year hiatus, Tainio made his comeback to the international team, immediately after his contract with the Red Bulls expired.\n\n==Managerial career==\nOn 1 November 2018, Tainio was appointed as head coach of [[Ykk\u00f6nen]] side [[FC Haka]], having previously worked as a coach at the side.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fchaka.fi/?p=7532|title=Teemu Tainio valmis uusiin haasteisiin|publisher=[[FC Haka]]|date=1 November 2018|accessdate=5 June 2019|language=Finnish}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===International goals===\n''Finland's score first.''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! # !! Date !! Location !! Opponent !! Score!! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1. || 1 September 2001 || [[Tirana]], Albania || {{fb|ALB}} || 2\u20130 || Win || [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2002 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 2. || 6 September 2003 || [[Baku]], Azerbaijan || {{fb|AZE}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying]]\n|-\n| 3. || 11 October 2003 || [[Tampere]], Finland || {{fb|CAN}} || 3\u20132 || Win || Friendly\n|-\n| 4. || 16 November 2003 || [[Houston]], USA || {{fb|HON}} || 2\u20131 || Win || Friendly\n|-\n| 5. || 13 October 2004 || [[Amsterdam]], Netherlands || {{fb|NED}} || 1\u20133 || Loss || [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2006 FIFA World Cup qualification]]\n|-\n| 6. || 22 August 2007 || Tampere, Finland || {{fb|KAZ}} || 2\u20131 || Win || [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===International===\n\n{{updated|14 February 2015}}<ref>{{NFT player|id=2402|accessdate= }}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!colspan=\"3\"|[[Finland national football team|Finland national team]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1998||3||0\n|-\n|1999||1||0\n|-\n|2000||3||0\n|-\n|2001||4||1\n|-\n|2002||6||0\n|-\n|2003||6||3\n|-\n|2004||2||1\n|-\n|2005||8||0\n|-\n|2006||2||0\n|-\n|2007||6||1\n|-\n|2008||5||0\n|-\n|2009||4||0\n|-\n|2010||2||0\n|-\n|2011||0||0\n|-\n|2012||0||0\n|-\n|2013||9||0\n|-\n|2014||3||0\n|-\n!Total||64||6\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n'''FC Haka'''\n*[[Finnish Cup]]: [[1997 Finnish Cup|1997]]\n\n'''Auxerre'''\n*[[Intertoto Cup]]: [[1997 UEFA Intertoto Cup|1997]]\n*[[Coupe de France]]: [[2005 Coupe de France Final|2004\u201305]]\n\n'''Tottenham Hotspur'''\n*[[Football League Cup|League Cup]]: [[2007\u201308 Football Leagu